t describes hormonal changes during the early luteal phase?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Progesterone exerts negative feedback on GnRH pulse frequency","Follicle stimulating hormone levels increase","Luteinizing hormone levels increase","Oestradiol levels are at their lowest","Inhibin production decreases"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the early luteal phase, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogesterone\u003C/strong\u003E produced by the corpus luteum exerts negative feedback on the hypothalamus, which decreases gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) pulse frequency. This is in contrast to the surge phase where oestradiol provides positive feedback.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicle stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eluteinizing hormone\u003C/strong\u003E levels are both low during the luteal phase due to negative feedback from progesterone and inhibin. \u003Cstrong\u003EOestradiol\u003C/strong\u003E levels actually rise again during the early luteal phase as the corpus luteum produces both oestradiol and progesterone. \u003Cstrong\u003EInhibin\u003C/strong\u003E production increases during the luteal phase as it is produced by the corpus luteum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The luteal phase is characterised by progesterone negative feedback, decreased GnRH pulse frequency, low FSH levels, and high inhibin production.","Corpus luteum produces progesterone and inhibin during the luteal phase."],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Yo